      <article>
        <header><h2>Overview</h2></header>
        <p>
          M5 is a "batteries included" toolkit for building mobile apps in HTML5. It aims to
          be the easiest way to get a great mobile app built and deployed. The core
          components of the toolkit include:
          <ul>
            <li>UI toolkit - provided by <a href="http://jquerymobile.com">jQuery Mobile</a></li>
            <li>Local web server for development and testing</li>
            <li>Browser-based simulator</li>
            <li>Remote debugger</li>
            <li>Package manager</li>
            <li>Build and deploy system</li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>The lifecycle for building M5 apps should be very familiar to web developers:
          <ul>
            <li>Edit code</li>
            <li>Test in the browser, repeat</li>
            <li>Test on your mobile device</li>
            <li>Deploy to production</li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <header><h2>Getting started</h2></header>
        <p>Go to the <a href="/download">download</a> page for installation instructions. Install
          gives you the <code>m5</code> program which is the front-end for all services.
        </p>
        <p>Try <code>m5 tutorial</code> to open the tutorial docs in your browser. Once you've
          got your app built, just use <code>m5 deploy</code> to deploy it up to m5apps.org
          for distribution, or deploy it to your own web server.
        </p>
        <header><h2>Learning more</h2></header>
        <ul>
          <li>Watch some of the videos on this page.</li>
          <li>Read about the <a href="/about">M5 philosophy</a></li>
          <li>Dig into the <a href="/docs">documentation</a></li>
          <li><a href="/browse">Browse</a> some of the apps built with M5</li>
        </ul>
      </articl>
